dev.marksman.collectionviews

Interface Vector<A>

  • Type Parameters:
    A - the element type
    All Superinterfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<A>, java.util.RandomAccess
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    ImmutableNonEmptyVector<A>, ImmutableVector<A>, NonEmptyVector<A>

    public interface Vector<A>
extends java.lang.Iterable<A>, java.util.RandomAccess
    A finite, ordered view of a collection that guarantees the following:
    • A size method that executes in O(1).
    • A get method that retrieves an element by index in O(1).
    • An isEmpty method that executes in O(1).
    • Iteration will always terminate.
    • Protected from mutation by the bearer.
    • The bearer cannot gain access to a reference to the underlying collection.

    Additionally, the ability to transform the Vector to new Vectors, without affecting or copying the underlying collection, is provided through the following methods:

    • fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A, ? extends B>)
    • take(int)
    • drop(int)
    • slice(int, int)

    While Vector does implement Iterable, it does not implement Collection. If you need to convert the Vector to a Collection, you will need to make a copy. Consider using Lambda's toCollection function to accomplish this.

      • fmap

        default <B> Vector<B> fmap(com.jnape.palatable.lambda.functions.Fn1<? super A,? extends B> f)
        Maps a function over the elements in a Vector and returns a new Vector of the same size (but possibly a different type).

        Does not make any copies of underlying data structures.

        This method is stack-safe, so a Vector can be mapped as many times as the heap permits.

        Type Parameters:
        B - The type of the elements contained in the output Vector.
        Parameters:
        f - a function from A to B. This function should be referentially transparent and not perform side-effects. It may be called zero or more times for each element.
        Returns:
        a Vector<B> of the same size

      • take

        default Vector<A> take(int count)
        Returns a new Vector that contains at most the first count elements of this Vector.

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

        Use caution when taking a small slice of a huge Vector, as the smaller slice will hold onto a reference of the larger one, and will prevent it from being GC'ed. To avoid this situation, use copyTakeFromIterable(int, java.lang.Iterable<A>) instead.

        Parameters:
        count - the maximum number of elements to take from the Vector. Must be >= 0. May exceed size of Vector.
        Returns:
        a Vector<A> containing between 0 and count elements

        Does not make copies of any underlying data structures.

      • wrap

        static <A> Vector<A> wrap(A[] underlying)
        Creates a Vector that wraps an array.

        Does not make any copies of the given array. The Vector will hold on to a reference to the array, but will never alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this Vector will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying array, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the array, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to the array can still mutate it. Use copyFromArray(A[]) instead if you want to avoid this situation.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        underlying - array to wrap
        Returns:
        a Vector<A>

      • wrap

        static <A> Vector<A> wrap(java.util.List<A> underlying)
        Creates a Vector that wraps a List.

        Does not make any copies of the given List. The Vector will hold a reference to the given List, but will not alter it in any way.

        Since bearers of this Vector will be unable to mutate or gain access to the underlying List, it is safe to share.

        Since this does not make a copy of the List, be aware that anyone that holds a direct reference to the List can still mutate it. Mutating the List is not advised. Operations that change the size of the underlying List will result in unpredictable behavior. Use copyAllFromIterable(java.lang.Iterable<A>) if you want to avoid this situation.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        underlying - List to wrap
        Returns:
        a Vector<A>

        static <A> Vector<A> takeFromIterable(int count,
                                      java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Builds a Vector from an Iterable.

        Will only make a copy of the data if necessary. If source is a List or another Vector, the data won't be copied.

        If you require an ImmutableVector, see copyTakeFromIterable(int, java.lang.Iterable<A>), which will always perform a copy instead of wrapping.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        count - maximum number of elements to take from source. Must be >= 0. May exceed the number of elements in source, in which case, all of the elements available will be taken.
        source - any Iterable, even those that are potentially infinite
        Returns:
        a Vector<A>

      • copyAllFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copyAllFromIterable(java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector from any Iterable.

        The entire Iterable will be eagerly iterated, so be careful not to pass in an infinite Iterable or this method will not terminate.

        If necessary to guarantee immutability, this method will make a copy of the data provided. If source already is an ImmutableVector, it will be returned directly.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly in its entirety
        Returns:
        an ImmutableVector<A>

      • copyTakeFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copyTakeFromIterable(int count,
                                                   java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector from any Iterable, but consuming a maximum number of elements.

        The Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only up to a maximum of count elements. If count elements are not available, then the all of the elements available will be returned.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, unless source is an ImmutableVector and its size is less than or equal to count, in which case it will be returned directly.

        If source is an ImmutableVector that is greater than count in size, a copy will always be made, therefore making it memory-safe to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        count - the maximum number of elements to consume from the source. Must be >= 0.
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly for up to count elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableVector that contains at most count elements.

      • copySliceFromIterable

        static <A> ImmutableVector<A> copySliceFromIterable(int startIndex,
                                                    int endIndexExclusive,
                                                    java.lang.Iterable<A> source)
        Constructs a new ImmutableVector slice from an Iterable.

        The Iterable will be eagerly iterated, but only for the number of elements needed to fulfill the requested slice. If not enough elements are not available, then this method yields as many elements that were available.

        This method will make a copy of the data provided, except in the case startIndex is 0 and source is an ImmutableVector whose size is less than or equal to count, in which case it will be returned directly.

        It is memory-safe to use this method to take a small slice of a huge Vector that you no longer need.

        Type Parameters:
        A - the element type
        Parameters:
        startIndex - the index of the element to begin the slice. Must be >= 0. May exceed the size of the Iterable, in which case an empty ImmutableVector will be returned.
        endIndexExclusive - the end index (exclusive) of the slice. Must be >= startIndex. May exceed the size of the Iterable, in which case the slice will contain as many elements as available.
        source - an Iterable<A> that will be iterated eagerly for up to endIndexExclusive elements. It is safe for source to be infinite.
        Returns:
        an ImmutableVector<A> that contains at most endIndexExclusive - startIndex elements.
